Did you know that healthy salmon populations indicate the health of both our rivers and oceans? That is why Fundy National Park has monitored Inner Bay of Fundy Salmon populations for over 25 years as part of the National iBoF Salmon Recovery program. Together with its partners, Parks Canada is trying to understand what is contributing to the salmon’s demise and what needs to be done to save them. Learn more: http://ow.ly/yw7d300mR0H World Fish Migration Day 
@WorldFishMigrationDay

Environment and Climate Change Canada is proud to work with the Nature Conservancy of Canada to expand the preservation of forested lands around Saint-Hippolyte, Quebec. The Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission can help! Highway 15 crosses the Island of Montréal from north to south. 

This major road is part of a network that serves the vast majority of the Montréal suburban area. It carries over 112,000 vehicles a day and maintenance of the surface of this part of the highway had become essential to traffic and user safety.

Thanks to federal financial support 7.7 kilometres of the highway between Mirabel and Blainville was repaired. 

Motorists now travel a safer, more fluid highway that preserves an essential link in the economic development of the region.

caption_original:
Have you ever wondered how many species of insects there are? Are all bugs insects? How does bug science help Canadians? How do you keep an archive of millions of bugs?

Let’s talk about bugs! We’re hosting a tweet chat with the curators of the Canadian National Collection of Insects, Arachnids and Nematodes (CNC), one of the largest collections of its kind in the world. The CNC serves Canadian scientists who investigate problems in the fields of agriculture, biodiversity, genetics, biological control and other various forms of integrated pest management, and is part of an international network for other researchers, educators and policy-makers. And they want to chat with you on Twitter about the work they do! 

You don’t need a Twitter account to follow along, but you will need one to ask a question or participate in the chat with our scientists.
caption_cleaned: Have you ever wondered how many species of insects there are? Are all bugs insects? How does bug science help Canadians? How do you keep an archive of millions of bugs? The CNC serves Canadian scientists who investigate problems in the fields of agriculture, biodiversity, genetics, biological control and other various forms of integrated pest management, and is part of an international network for other researchers, educators and policy-makers. And they want to chat with you on Twitter about the work they do!
